Commands learned today:
1. gzip -- compresses files into a .gz file using algorithms i dont know about
--> gzip -d uncompresses a file
2. gunzip -- decompresses files
3. tar -- creates archives
--> flags dictate intent.
tar -c creates files
tar -x extracts files from an archive
tar -f lets you name a file to make into an archive 
tar -l lists the files in an archive without extracting them
tar -z allows compression of files without having to use gzip
4. nano -> really useful command, opens up a text editor for you to open files. creates files if no name matches
5. alias -> lets you create short hand for useful commands. e.g., alias count = 'echo {1..99}'
-> put permanent aliases in .bashrc, import using source
-> '' vs "". the former is situational, the latter is hard fixed
6. xargs -- an extension of piping, lets you pipe in results as arguments to commands that dont usually work using piping
7. ln -- lets you create either a hard link or a soft (symbolic) link
-> a link is a pointer to a file. for example, desktop icons 
-> hard link: if original file is deleted, hard link remains
-> ln -s -> soft link: if original file is deleted, symlink is broken
8. who -> shows current user and log in time
9. su -- lets you log in into another user in a tab
-> 'su -' allows you to log in literally into another user
10. sudo -- allows you to perform root commands 
11. passwd -- allows you to change or do other stuff with a users password
12. chown -- chown owner:group filename -- allows you to change the owner or group of a file
13. chmod -- chmod ugo+-rwx, =, all, file name -- allows you to change permissions of files
-- learned how permissions work
